<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920108-0026</DOCNO><DOCID>920108-0026.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Hughes Official Enters   Guilty Plea in Intelsat Case</HL><DATE>01/08/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   GM GMH</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)MICHIGAN (MI)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A former vice president of Hughes AircraftCo. pleaded guilty to obstructing justice in connection withallegations that he bribed a former senior official of theInternational Telecommunications Satellite Organization.   The U.S. attorney's office here said the former executive,Paul Visher, entered the plea in federal court here Monday.According to a 10-count indictment filed last September, Mr.Visher made payments of more than $300,000 to the Intelsatofficial, Jose Alegrett, between 1974 and 1986. The paymentsallegedly were made through a series of bogus consultants.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Visher was a senior official in the Hughes group thatsold satellites to Intelsat, an international satelliteconsortium. Mr. Alegrett, who rose to become the No. 2official at Intelsat, was named as an unindictedco-conspirator in the case. He was convicted of fraud in 1988in connection with a separate scam involving the constructionof Intelsat's headquarters. He served 16 months in prison.   Mr. Visher, who will be sentenced in March, couldn't bereached for comment. He left Hughes, a unit of General MotorsCorp., in 1987.</TEXT></DOC>